\subsection*{Abstract} These notes are an extended version of a talk given by the author at the conference ``Analytic Number Theory and Related Areas'', held at Research Institute for Mathematical Sciences, Kyoto University in November 2015. We are interested in ``$L$-data'', an axiomatic framework for $L$-functions introduced by Andrew Booker in 2013 \cite{LFAD}. Associated to each $L$-datum, one has a real number invariant known as the degree. Conjecturally the degree $d$ is an integer, and if $d\in\mathbb{N}$ then the $L$-datum is that of a ${\operatorname{GL}}_n(\mathbb{A}_F)$-automorphic representation for $n\in\mathbb{N}$ and a number field $F$ (if $F=\mathbb{Q}$, then $n=d$.). This statement was shown to be true for $0\leq d<\frac{5}{3}$ by Booker in his pioneering paper \cite{LFAD}, and in these notes we consider an extension of his methods to $0\leq d<2$. This is simultaneously a generalisation of Booker's result and the results and techniques of Kaczorowski--Perelli in the Selberg class \cite{OTSOSCVII}. Furthermore, we consider applications to zeros of automorphic $L$-functions. In these notes we review Booker's results and announce new ones to appear elsewhere shortly \cite{COLDLD}.
